	<Folder>
		<name>Mega-refineries</name>
		<Placemark id="0BAD6318AD3E92734D19">
			<name>Gazprom Neft Omsk Refinery</name>
			<description>Refinery: Gazprom Neft Omsk Refinery
Classification: Mega-refinery
Location: Omsk, southwestern Siberia, Russia
Owner: Gazprom Neft
Capacity: Approximately 22 million tonnes per year, equivalent to roughly 440,000–460,000 barrels per day
Main feedstocks: Russian crude supplied mainly through the domestic pipeline network
Main products: Gasoline, diesel, jet fuel, LPG, bitumen, petroleum coke, sulfur and petrochemical feedstocks
Markets: Primarily Siberia, the Urals and other Russian domestic markets, with selected exports to neighbouring countries
Recent data: In July 2026, a Ukrainian drone attack damaged major crude-distillation units and temporarily halted refinery operations. The site processed about 22 million tonnes of crude in 2024, producing roughly 5 million tonnes of gasoline and 8 million tonnes of diesel.
Strategic role: Russia’s largest refinery by crude-processing capacity and a critical supplier of transport fuels to Siberia and the domestic Russian market
Risks: Long-range drone attacks, unit fires, pipeline disruption, sanctions, equipment-replacement constraints, severe Siberian winter conditions and prolonged maintenance outages</description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>73.29601615501225</longitude>
				<latitude>55.07671198744744</latitude>
				<altitude>132.7924446205419</altitude>
				<heading>348.1667833384008</heading>
				<tilt>0</tilt>
				<gx:fovy>35</gx:fovy>
				<range>25845.59989350848</range>
				<altitudeMode>absolute</altitudeMode>
			</LookAt>
			<styleUrl>#msn_volcano</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>73.23182490608777,55.0636869098589,121.4742082917068</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark id="067D0BFC453F60C99838">
			<name>MiRO Karlsruhe Refinery — Mineraloelraffinerie Oberrhein</name>
			<description>Refinery: MiRO — Mineraloelraffinerie Oberrhein
Classification: Mega-refinery
Location: Karlsruhe-Knielingen, Baden-Württemberg, Germany
Operator: MiRO Mineraloelraffinerie Oberrhein GmbH &amp; Co. KG
Shareholders: Shell 32.25%, ExxonMobil/Esso 25%, Rosneft Deutschland 24% and Phillips 66 18.75%. Rosneft’s German assets remain under German state trusteeship.
Capacity: Approximately 14.9–15 million tonnes per year, equivalent to roughly 300,000 barrels per day
Main feedstocks: Diverse imported crude oils delivered mainly from the Mediterranean port of Trieste through the Transalpine Pipeline — TAL
Main products: Gasoline, diesel, heating oil, jet-fuel components, LPG, propylene, bitumen, sulfur and petrochemical feedstocks
Markets: Southern and southwestern Germany, especially Baden-Württemberg, Bavaria and the Upper Rhine region
Infrastructure: Around 19 crude-oil tanks with approximately 730,000 m³ of crude-storage capacity, plus more than 350 tanks across the wider complex.
Strategic role: Germany’s largest refinery. MiRO processes around 15 million tonnes of crude annually, supplies approximately 10 million people, and states that about one-third of the gasoline sold in Germany originates from the site.
Risks: Dependence on the TAL pipeline, refinery-unit outages, Rhine logistics disruption, high European energy and carbon costs, sanctions-related ownership uncertainty and prolonged maintenance shutdowns</description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>8.3364487</longitude>
				<latitude>49.0529923</latitude>
				<altitude>0</altitude>
				<heading>0</heading>
				<tilt>0</tilt>
				<gx:fovy>35</gx:fovy>
				<range>1573.597768357931</range>
				<altitudeMode>relativeToGround</altitudeMode>
			</LookAt>
			<styleUrl>#msn_volcano3</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<altitudeMode>relativeToGround</altitudeMode>
				<coordinates>8.336358799999999,49.0530041,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark id="0EE419DEE93EB14F572B">
			<name>Paraguaná Refinery Complex</name>
			<description>Refinery: Paraguaná Refining Center — Amuay &amp; Cardón
Classification: Super-refinery / mega-refinery by nominal capacity, but severely underutilized
Location: Paraguaná Peninsula, Falcón State, Venezuela
Owner: Petróleos de Venezuela S.A. (PDVSA)
Nominal capacity: Approximately 955,000 barrels per day for the Amuay and Cardón refineries; some broader figures reach about 971,000 b/d when the Bajo Grande asphalt facility is included.
Main feedstocks: Venezuelan light, medium and heavy crude oils, including grades from western Venezuela and the Orinoco region
Main products: Gasoline, diesel, jet fuel, LPG, naphtha, fuel oil, asphalt and petrochemical feedstocks
Markets: Primarily Venezuela’s domestic market; historically also Caribbean and regional export markets
Recent data: In February 2026, the complex processed about 287,000 b/d after recovering from a power outage. By April 2026, throughput had fallen to roughly 237,000 b/d, with only four crude-distillation units and one catalytic cracker operating.
Recent development: A June 2026 PDVSA–Repsol agreement envisaged additional crude production partly to increase feedstock supply to the Paraguaná complex.
Strategic role: Venezuela’s largest refining complex and the country’s most important source of domestic transport fuels
Risks: Chronic equipment failures, power outages, fires, insufficient maintenance, sanctions, shortages of spare parts and diluents, crude-supply constraints and very low utilization</description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>-70.21436687959421</longitude>
				<latitude>11.63362088754329</latitude>
				<altitude>21.40784376444955</altitude>
				<heading>0</heading>
				<tilt>0</tilt>
				<gx:fovy>35</gx:fovy>
				<range>6459.276534434175</range>
				<altitudeMode>absolute</altitudeMode>
			</LookAt>
			<styleUrl>#msn_volcano</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>-70.22578419359186,11.63155965959824,21.0681920978475</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark id="0FAB4BEFE33EB859A0B8">
			<name>ExxonMobil Antwerp Refinery</name>
			<description>Refinery: ExxonMobil Antwerp Refinery
Classification: Mega-refinery
Location: Port of Antwerp-Bruges, Belgium
Owner: ExxonMobil, through ExxonMobil Petroleum &amp; Chemical
Capacity: Approximately 320,000 barrels per day
Main feedstocks: Flexible imported crude slate, ranging from light sweet to heavier sour grades, delivered through Antwerp’s marine-terminal and pipeline network
Main products: LPG, gasoline, naphtha, kerosene/jet-fuel components, diesel, gasoil, fuel oil, sulfur and petrochemical feedstocks
Markets: Belgium, the Netherlands, Germany, France and other Northwest European markets
Recent data: Production was scheduled to stop from 29 June to 3 July 2026 because of industrial action. ExxonMobil also paused a planned Antwerp chemical-recycling investment in 2025 amid uncertainty over proposed EU recycled-content rules.
Strategic role: One of Europe’s largest and most complex integrated refining and petrochemical sites, strategically located within the Antwerp trading, storage and pipeline hub
Risks: Labour disruption, refinery-unit outages, Antwerp port congestion, Rhine and pipeline logistics interruption, high European energy and carbon costs, and pressure on regional refining margins</description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>4.343410939707557</longitude>
				<latitude>51.25685391177716</latitude>
				<altitude>2.515600942033105</altitude>
				<heading>0</heading>
				<tilt>0</tilt>
				<gx:fovy>35</gx:fovy>
				<range>2113.435120219365</range>
				<altitudeMode>absolute</altitudeMode>
			</LookAt>
			<styleUrl>#msn_volcano2</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>4.340578162287001,51.25641690622821,2.515883136095622</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark id="0EE5A8447F3EB85EEA70">
			<name>TotalEnergies Antwerp Refinery &amp; Petrochemical Platform</name>
			<description>Refinery: TotalEnergies Antwerp Refinery &amp; Petrochemical Platform
Classification: Mega-refinery
Location: Port of Antwerp-Bruges, Belgium
Owner: TotalEnergies
Capacity: Approximately 338,000 barrels per day
Main feedstocks: Imported crude oils and intermediate refinery streams delivered through Antwerp’s marine, storage and pipeline network
Main products: Gasoline, diesel, jet fuel, LPG, naphtha, fuel oil, petrochemical feedstocks and high-density polyethylene
Markets: Belgium, the Netherlands, Germany, France and other Northwest European markets
Recent data: TotalEnergies launched co-processing capacity for about 50,000 tonnes/year of sustainable aviation fuel, with plans to increase this to roughly 80,000 tonnes/year. The platform is also preparing to use about 15,000 tonnes/year of green hydrogen from a planned electrolyser project.
Recent development: TotalEnergies plans to close the platform’s oldest steam cracker by the end of 2027, while maintaining the newer cracker and the refinery.
Strategic role: TotalEnergies’ largest integrated refining and petrochemical platform in Europe, strategically located in the Antwerp–Rotterdam–Amsterdam trading hub.
Risks: High European energy and carbon costs, weak petrochemical margins, refinery or cracker outages, Antwerp port congestion, labour disruption and tightening environmental regulations</description>
