			<name>Galveston Bay Refinery</name>
			<description>Refinery: Marathon Galveston Bay Refinery
Classification: Mega-refinery
Location: Texas City, Texas, United States
Owner: Marathon Petroleum Corporation
Capacity: About 631,000 barrels per calendar day; the EIA reports roughly 678,000 barrels per stream day as of January 2026
Main feedstocks: Flexible crude slate, including U.S. light crude, medium and heavy crude, and imported grades
Main products: Gasoline, diesel, jet fuel, natural gas liquids, petrochemical feedstocks, heavy fuel oil and propane
Markets: U.S. Gulf Coast and inland U.S. markets, with access to international exports by pipeline, barge, rail, truck and ocean tanker
Recent data: A June 2025 fire damaged a 64,000 b/d residual hydrotreater, reducing output at related units; repairs extended into September 2025. In early 2026, Marathon also reached a labor agreement that avoided a strike at the site.
Strategic role: Marathon’s largest refinery and one of the largest U.S. refining complexes, located near the entrance to the Houston Ship Channel with strong export access
Risks: Gulf Coast hurricanes, flooding, fires and unit outages, labor disruption, Houston Ship Channel congestion, environmental regulation and volatile refining margins</description>
