		<Placemark id="077D626E7D40213C6606">
			<name>Equinor Mongstad Refinery, Industrial Site &amp; Crude Oil Terminal</name>
			<description>Site: Mongstad Industrial Site, Refinery &amp; Crude Oil Terminal
Classification: Large refinery and major strategic export terminal — not a mega-refinery
Location: Mongstad, Vestland, Norway
Owner: The refinery is operated by Equinor. The Mongstad crude terminal, MTDA, is owned by Equinor (65%) and the Norwegian state (35%), with Equinor as operator.
Refining capacity: About 180,000 barrels per day, so the refinery itself belongs in Large Refineries, not Mega-refineries.
Main feedstocks: Norwegian North Sea crude, including volumes from Johan Sverdrup, Troll, Gjøa, Kristin and Vega, delivered mainly by pipeline.
Main products: Gasoline, diesel, jet fuel, LPG, naphtha, gasoil, heavy fuel oil, sulphur and petroleum coke.
Markets: Norway, Europe, North America and Asia, through the refinery and the adjacent crude-export terminal.
Terminal capacity: Approximately 9.44 million barrels of underground crude storage. Around 40% of Equinor-operated Norwegian shelf oil, including the state’s share, is stored there before export.
Recent data: A major maintenance shutdown took place in 2025. Equinor later investigated a fatal lifting accident and a separate benzene-exposure incident, introducing stronger safety and risk-control measures in 2026.
Strategic role: Norway’s only refinery and one of its most important crude-storage, processing and marine-export hubs.
Risks: North Sea weather, pipeline interruption, terminal congestion, refinery outages, industrial accidents, fire, chemical exposure and disruption to offshore-field exports.</description>
