			<styleUrl>#msn_R2</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>103.7668729626669,1.233288599538126,6.555920423163444</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark id="03CC2AA86E3EB75AA49C">
			<name>MOL Danube Refinery</name>
			<description>Refinery: MOL Danube Refinery
Classification: Large refinery — not a mega-refinery
Location: Százhalombatta, near Budapest, Hungary
Owner: MOL Group
Capacity: About 8.1 million tonnes per year, equivalent to roughly 165,000 barrels per day.
Main feedstocks: Traditionally Russian crude delivered through the Druzhba pipeline, with alternative supply available through the Adria pipeline from the Adriatic coast.
Main products: Gasoline, diesel, jet fuel, LPG, heating oil, bitumen, sulfur and petrochemical feedstocks
Markets: Primarily Hungary and neighbouring Central European markets
Recent data: The refinery is currently operating at reduced capacity following an October 2025 fire affecting the AV3 crude-distillation unit. MOL expects repairs to be completed and full capacity restored in Q3 2026.
Low-carbon activity: A 10 MW electrolyser has entered operation at the site, with annual production capacity of approximately 1,600 tonnes of green hydrogen for refinery decarbonisation.
Strategic role: Hungary’s principal refinery and a critical fuel-supply hub for the domestic market
Risks: Druzhba pipeline disruption, dependence on Russian crude, Adria capacity constraints, refinery-unit outages, inland logistics limitations and high European energy and carbon costs</description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>18.89850153628964</longitude>
				<latitude>47.28434477978583</latitude>
