		<Placemark id="0676CCA4EB3EB791CB54">
			<name>ORLEN Unipetrol Litvínov Refinery</name>
			<description>Refinery: ORLEN Unipetrol Litvínov Refinery
Classification: Conventional refinery — not a mega-refinery
Location: Litvínov, Ústí nad Labem Region, Czech Republic
Owner: ORLEN Unipetrol, part of Poland’s ORLEN Group
Capacity: Approximately 5.8 million tonnes per year, equivalent to roughly 115,000–120,000 barrels per day
Main feedstocks: Historically Russian Urals crude through the Druzhba pipeline; since early 2025, the refinery has shifted to non-Russian crude blends delivered mainly through the TAL and IKL pipeline systems.
Main products: Gasoline, diesel, jet-fuel components, LPG, heating oil, sulfur and petrochemical feedstocks
Markets: Primarily the Czech Republic and neighbouring Central European markets
Recent data: In 2025, ORLEN completed technical preparations allowing Litvínov to process a wider range of crude grades and ended Russian crude deliveries to the refinery. The site suffered an emergency shutdown during the Czech power outage of July 2025, before fully resuming operations later that month.
Strategic role: Czechia’s largest refinery and a key element of the country’s transition away from Russian oil dependence
Risks: TAL/IKL pipeline disruption, power-grid failures, refinery outages, inland logistics constraints, high European energy and carbon costs, and difficulties adapting to changing crude qualities</description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>13.60541802658853</longitude>
