		<Placemark id="09C8EF4BC13EB8B1E0B0">
			<name>ExxonMobil Rotterdam Refinery</name>
			<description>Refinery: ExxonMobil Rotterdam Refinery
Classification: Large refinery — not a mega-refinery
Location: Rotterdam-Botlek, Netherlands
Owner: ExxonMobil, through Esso Nederland B.V.
Capacity: Approximately 190,000 barrels per day
Main feedstocks: Wide crude slate, from light low-sulfur grades to heavy high-sulfur crude, supplied by ship to Maasvlakte and Europoort tank farms, then transferred by pipeline to the refinery.
Main products: LPG, naphtha, kerosene, diesel, sulfur, petroleum coke, chemical feedstocks and high-quality Group II/II+ lubricant base oils.
Markets: Netherlands and wider Northwest European fuel, lubricant and petrochemical markets
Recent data: ExxonMobil paused a planned European chemical-recycling investment in 2025, including a Rotterdam project, because of uncertainty over proposed EU recycled-content rules.
Strategic role: Highly integrated refinery, aromatics and hydrogen complex; its 2019 hydrocracker upgrade improved energy efficiency by about 5% and made Rotterdam Europe’s only world-scale producer of Group II/II+ base stocks.
Risks: Rhine and port logistics disruption, refinery outages, high European energy and carbon costs, regulatory uncertainty and pressure on European refining margins</description>
