		<Placemark id="0A913C9C043EDC3F4AF1">
			<name>Rosneft Novokuibyshevsk Refinery</name>
			<description>Refinery: Rosneft Novokuibyshevsk Refinery
Classification: Large refinery — not a mega-refinery
Location: Novokuibyshevsk, Samara Oblast, Russia
Owner: Rosneft, as part of its Samara refining group
Capacity: 8.8 million tonnes per year, equivalent to roughly 175,000–180,000 barrels per day
Main feedstocks: Crude from the Orenburg region, Western Siberia and Rosneft’s Samara-region production
Main products: Gasoline, diesel, jet fuel, LPG, fuel oil, bitumen, sulfur and petrochemical intermediates
Markets: Mainly the Volga region and Russia’s domestic market, with some products historically supplied to export channels
Recent data: The refinery halted primary processing after a drone attack on 18 April 2026 and was still operating at reduced throughput in June 2026. In 2024, it processed about 5.74 million tonnes of crude, producing roughly 1.10 million tonnes of gasoline, 1.64 million tonnes of diesel and 1.27 million tonnes of fuel oil.
Strategic role: One of the main refineries in Russia’s Volga region, with catalytic cracking, delayed coking, reforming, isomerization and hydrotreatment capacity.
Risks: Drone attacks, fires, prolonged unit shutdowns, sanctions, difficulty sourcing replacement equipment, pipeline disruption and reduced operational reliability</description>
