		<Placemark id="035ECDB22B3F39E1E2F9">
			<name>Lanaz Refinery</name>
			<description>Refinery: Lanaz Refinery
Classification: Conventional refinery — not a mega-refinery
Location: Near Lajan village, approximately 18–20 km west of Erbil, Kurdistan Region of Iraq
Owner/Operator: Lanaz Company for Refineries and Refining of Petroleum Products, a privately operated Kurdistan-based company
Nominal capacity: Approximately 75,000 barrels per day according to the Kurdistan Regional Government. Some company and Honeywell publications have cited a design or processing capacity of up to 100,000 b/d.
Main feedstocks: Crude oil produced from fields in the Kurdistan Region of Iraq
Main products: Gasoline, diesel, naphtha, LPG, fuel oil and bitumen/asphalt
Production capacity: Up to approximately 1.7 million litres of gasoline per day and 5,000 tonnes per day of asphalt and other petroleum products, according to official inauguration figures.
Markets: Primarily Erbil and the Kurdistan Region’s domestic fuel market, with some bitumen and petroleum-product exports to regional and international markets
Technology: Modern conversion and clean-fuel processing technologies, including equipment and licensing supplied by Honeywell UOP.
Recent data: A drone strike in March 2026 caused a fire and led to a precautionary suspension of production while damage was assessed. Reports at the time indicated an effective operating rate of around 40,000 b/d, below nominal capacity.
Strategic role: One of the principal modern refineries serving the Erbil area, supporting regional gasoline and diesel supply and reducing dependence on imported refined products
Risks: Drone attacks, regional instability, interruptions to crude supply, local community tensions, fires, storage risks and uncertain utilization rates</description>
			<LookAt>
