		</Placemark>
		<Placemark id="0AF4D980803F39EAB110">
			<name>Baiji refinery</name>
			<description>Refinery: Baiji Refinery Complex — Al-Sumood Complex
Classification: Large refinery / mega-refinery by total complex capacity
Location: Baiji, Salah al-Din Governorate, approximately 200–250 km north of Baghdad, Iraq
Owner/Operator: North Refineries Company, under the Iraqi Ministry of Oil
Nominal capacity: Approximately 290,000–310,000 barrels per day for the complete refining complex
Current configuration: The complex historically comprised three main refining trains. A rehabilitated 150,000 b/d North Refinery restarted in February 2024 after nearly ten years out of operation, bringing the restored complex capacity to around 290,000 b/d at that stage.
Main feedstocks: Iraqi crude oil supplied through the national pipeline network, including crude from northern and central Iraqi fields
Main products: Gasoline, diesel, kerosene, jet fuel, LPG, naphtha, fuel oil, sulfur and other petroleum products
Markets: Primarily Iraq’s domestic market, especially Baghdad and the northern and central regions
Recent data: Rehabilitation has continued since the 2024 restart, and reporting in early 2026 indicated that Baiji’s restored processing capacity was contributing significantly to the rise in Iraq’s national refining capacity. A fire at a fuel-production unit in February 2026 was contained, although one fatality was reported.
Strategic role: Historically Iraq’s largest refining center and a critical asset for reducing gasoline and diesel imports and strengthening domestic fuel security
Risks: Ageing and war-damaged infrastructure, fires, power failures, pipeline interruptions, security threats, maintenance constraints and differences between nominal capacity and actual throughput</description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>43.4933125</longitude>
				<latitude>35.0054375</latitude>
