		</Placemark>
		<Placemark id="0A97B2A6A03F39ECF13C">
			<name>Midland Refineries Company – Daura Refinery</name>
			<description>Refinery: Midland Refineries Company – Daura Refinery
Classification: Conventional refinery — not a mega-refinery
Location: Daura industrial district, southern Baghdad, on the Tigris River, Iraq
Owner/Operator: Midland Refineries Company (MRC), a state-owned company under the Iraqi Ministry of Oil
Nominal capacity: Approximately 110,000 barrels per day
Recent operating level: Historically often below nominal capacity because of ageing equipment, maintenance constraints and unit outages
Main feedstocks: Iraqi crude supplied from central and northern fields through the national pipeline network
Main products: Gasoline, diesel/gas oil, kerosene, jet-fuel components, LPG, fuel oil, naphtha, bitumen and other petroleum products
Markets: Primarily Baghdad and central Iraq’s domestic fuel market
Configuration: Mainly a hydroskimming refinery, with a relatively modest complexity level compared with newer conversion refineries
Recent development: MRC has continued rehabilitation and modernization work, including power-generation, reforming and diesel-hydrotreating infrastructure. The restart of an 18 MW gas-power unit in 2024 improved the site’s internal electricity reliability.
Strategic role: One of Iraq’s oldest refineries and the principal refining asset serving Baghdad and the central region
Risks: Ageing infrastructure, limited conversion capacity, electricity failures, fires, pipeline interruptions, urban environmental impact and differences between nominal capacity and actual throughput</description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>44.4249515</longitude>
				<latitude>33.2780815</latitude>
