		<Placemark id="0B2BEEDECD3F32C45703">
			<name>Houston Ship Channel / Buffalo Bayou Industrial Corridor</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<p class="isSelectedEnd"><span>This location is part of the Houston Ship Channel industrial corridor, one of the largest concentrations of refining, petrochemical, storage, and marine terminal infrastructure in the world. The waterway visible here is Buffalo Bayou, which has been widened and deepened to form the upper section of the Houston Ship Channel. It allows ocean-going ships and inland barges to reach industrial facilities deep inside the Houston metropolitan area.</span><br></p><p class="isSelectedEnd"><span>The facilities along this corridor include crude oil refineries, petrochemical plants, chemical storage terminals, refined-product terminals, LPG and NGL handling facilities, pipeline interconnections, rail yards, tank farms, ship docks, and barge docks. The many circular tanks visible from satellite imagery are above-ground storage tanks used for crude oil, gasoline, diesel, jet fuel, fuel oil, chemicals, petrochemical feedstocks, and other bulk liquids. The dense pipe racks, process units, columns, heaters, and flare systems belong to refineries and petrochemical plants that convert crude oil and natural gas liquids into transportation fuels, plastics feedstocks, solvents, and industrial chemicals.</span><br></p><p class="isSelectedEnd"><span>This area is different from the Mont Belvieu NGL/LPG benchmark hub, which is located farther east/northeast near the Barbers Hill salt dome. Mont Belvieu is primarily a storage, fractionation, and pipeline pricing hub for natural gas liquids such as ethane, propane, butane, and natural gasoline. The Houston Ship Channel, by contrast, is the marine export and industrial processing corridor. Products produced, stored, or priced at inland hubs such as Mont Belvieu often move by pipeline to terminals along the Houston Ship Channel, where they can be loaded onto ships for export.</span><br></p><p class="isSelectedEnd"><span>The Houston Ship Channel functions as a critical link between inland U.S. energy production and global markets. Crude oil, refined products, petrochemicals, chemicals, LPG, and other bulk commodities move through this corridor by pipeline, rail, truck, barge, and seagoing vessel. The channel connects the industrial areas of Houston, Pasadena, Galena Park, Deer Park, Baytown, and nearby communities to Galveston Bay and the Gulf of Mexico.</span><br></p><p><span>The concentration of tanks, docks, pipelines, and processing units visible here reflects Houston’s role as a major global energy and petrochemical hub. This corridor supports refining, chemical manufacturing, export logistics, and international bulk commodity trade, making it one of the most strategically important industrial waterways in the United States.</span><br></p><div><br></div>]]></description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>-95.13269279395078</longitude>
				<latitude>29.74212329689966</latitude>
