	</Folder>
	<Folder>
		<name>Ammonia production sites</name>
		<Placemark id="0FC064381E402B29DCAE">
			<name>Renewable ammonia plant in construction</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div>AM Green is building a 500,000 mt/y renewable ammonia plant&nbsp; with a second phase planned later. Together the project would reach 1 million mt/y.<br></div><div><br></div><div>From platts :</div><p>The important point is not only the volume. It is that AM Green reached <b>FID</b>.<br></p><p><b>FID = Final Investment Decision.</b><br></p><p>That means the company has formally decided to proceed with the project, commit capital, and move into construction/execution.<br></p><p>In this sector, many projects are announced, but fewer reach FID. So AM Green is saying:<br></p><blockquote><p>“Even if demand is slow, there are not many real projects that can supply compliant renewable ammonia. If we are ready, we may benefit from scarcity.”<br></p></blockquote><div><br></div>]]></description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>82.2814575150484</longitude>
				<latitude>17.01440262913634</latitude>
				<altitude>26.64753690294258</altitude>
				<heading>0</heading>
				<tilt>0</tilt>
				<gx:fovy>34.99999688960803</gx:fovy>
				<range>3207.545008665767</range>
				<altitudeMode>absolute</altitudeMode>
			</LookAt>
			<styleUrl>#msn_icon?color=00796b&amp;id=2000&amp;scale=400</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<coordinates>82.28033268426049,17.01535870957651,26.30636801461603</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark id="0FA5410A653F22C64405">
			<name>Tampa ammonia terminal</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<p>The “Tampa ammonia terminal” usually refers to the large anhydrous ammonia import, storage, and transfer facilities at <span class="hover:entity-accent entity-underline inline cursor-pointer align-baseline"><span class="whitespace-normal">Port Tampa Bay</span></span> in <span class="hover:entity-accent entity-underline inline cursor-pointer align-baseline"><span class="whitespace-normal">Tampa</span></span>. These terminals are part of the fertilizer and chemical supply chain in the southeastern United States.<br></p><p>The best-known facilities are:<br></p><ul><li><b>Hooker’s Point Ammonia Terminal</b> — historically operated by companies including CF Industries, Yara, Mosaic, and now Tampa Port Services.<br></li><li><b>Port Sutton Ammonia Terminal</b> — another ammonia handling/storage site near the port industrial area.<br></li></ul><p>What these terminals do:<br></p><ul><li>Receive <b>anhydrous ammonia (NH₃)</b> by ship.<br></li><li>Store it in very large refrigerated tanks.<br></li><li>Transfer it via pipelines, railcars, trucks, or barges.<br></li><li>Supply Florida’s phosphate fertilizer industry, especially companies like Mosaic.<br></li></ul><p>Why Tampa is important:<br></p><ul><li>Tampa Bay is one of the main fertilizer export/import hubs in the U.S.<br></li><li>Central Florida has major phosphate mining and fertilizer production operations.<br></li><li>Imported ammonia is a key ingredient for making phosphate fertilizers.<br></li></ul><p>A notable feature is the ammonia pipeline network running from Tampa port facilities into Central Florida fertilizer plants.<br></p><p>In commodity trading, “Tampa ammonia” is also used as a benchmark pricing point for ammonia imports into the U.S. Gulf fertilizer market.<br></p><div><br></div>]]></description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>-82.42413834401903</longitude>
				<latitude>27.90229463780023</latitude>
				<altitude>4.675762534799095</altitude>
				<heading>26.01541549207407</heading>
				<tilt>0</tilt>
				<gx:fovy>34.99999976200483</gx:fovy>
				<range>3095.601653857157</range>
				<altitudeMode>absolute</altitudeMode>
			</LookAt>
			<styleUrl>#msn_icon?color=00796b&amp;id=2000&amp;scale=400</styleUrl>
			<ExtendedData>
				<SchemaData schemaUrl="#__managed_schema0">
					<SimpleData name="12383F7AA63F22C64405">0</SimpleData>
				</SchemaData>
			</ExtendedData>
			<Point>
				<extrude>1</extrude>
				<coordinates>-82.42339024440813,27.90486727839101,1.872696362167723</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark id="0B6901C6983F22D4E303">
			<name>Point Lisas Industrial Estate (Ammonia facilities)</name>
			<description>Facility: Point Lisas Industrial Estate – Ammonia Production Complex
Classification: Major natural-gas-based ammonia and fertilizer hub
Location: Point Lisas, Couva, west coast of Trinidad, Trinidad and Tobago
Estate/Port operator: Point Lisas Industrial Port Development Corporation — PLIPDECO
Main operators: Proman, Nutrien, Yara/Tringen and Point Lisas Nitrogen Limited
Main feedstock: Natural gas supplied from Trinidad and Tobago’s offshore gas fields through the national pipeline network
Main products: Anhydrous ammonia, urea, urea-ammonium-nitrate solution, melamine and related nitrogen fertilizers
Ammonia capacity: The Point Lisas ammonia industry comprises about 11 plants with total nominal capacity of approximately 5.2 million tonnes per year.
Key facilities: Nutrien’s nitrogen complex, Proman’s CNC and N2000 plants, Yara/Tringen facilities, the AUM complex and the Point Lisas Nitrogen plant
Proman capacity: The CNC and N2000 ammonia plants together have approximately 1.3 million tonnes per year of production capacity.
Point Lisas Nitrogen capacity: Approximately 650,000 tonnes per year; the plant is one of the estate’s large single-train ammonia facilities.
Port infrastructure: Ammonia and fertilizer products are exported through dedicated marine berths connected to the production and storage facilities. PLIPDECO coordinates vessel movements, while specialized berths are operated within the National Energy port system.
Main export markets: United States, Latin America, Europe, the Caribbean and other Atlantic markets
Industrial integration: Carbon dioxide generated during ammonia production is supplied to neighbouring methanol, urea and chemical plants, creating a highly integrated petrochemical cluster
Strategic role: One of the world’s most concentrated ammonia-production and export hubs and a central pillar of Trinidad and Tobago’s downstream natural-gas industry
Recent operational issues: Production has been affected by domestic natural-gas shortages, weak plant utilization and port-access disputes. Nutrien initiated a controlled shutdown of its Trinidad nitrogen operations in October 2025 following restrictions on port access.
Risks: Natural-gas supply curtailment, ageing plants, port-access disputes, ammonia leaks, fire and explosion hazards, hurricanes, international fertilizer-price volatility and carbon-emissions regulation</description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>-61.47459162426281</longitude>
				<latitude>10.39001091184189</latitude>
				<altitude>6.989576623120575</altitude>
