		<Placemark id="0374211D203F382D045A">
			<name>Kandla Green Hydrogen &amp; Renewable Ammonia Hub</name>
			<description>Facility: Kandla Green Hydrogen &amp; Renewable Ammonia Hub
Classification: Major green hydrogen and green ammonia production hub / renewable-energy industrial project
Location: Deendayal Port, Kandla, Kutch District, Gujarat, India
Developer framework: Deendayal Port Authority, with industrial projects led by companies including L&amp;T Energy GreenTech, Reliance Industries, AM Green Hydrogen and Welspun New Energy
Main products: Green hydrogen, renewable ammonia and potentially other hydrogen derivatives for industrial use, export and marine fuel
Production process: Renewable electricity powers electrolysers that split water into hydrogen and oxygen. The hydrogen is then combined with nitrogen in an ammonia-synthesis unit to produce low-carbon ammonia
Renewable-energy supply: Primarily solar and wind electricity sourced from Gujarat and other renewable-generation zones
Planned hub capacity: Developers allocated land at Kandla are collectively expected to produce about 5.5 million tonnes per year of green hydrogen and green ammonia by 2030–31.
Water supply: A planned 300 million-litre-per-day desalination plant is intended to support the water requirements of the hydrogen-production facilities
Main markets: India, Europe and Asia, with strong potential for exports to Japan and Singapore and for use as low-carbon marine fuel
Port integration: Located within Deendayal Port, allowing ammonia storage, ship loading, bunkering and export through the Arabian Sea
Strategic role: One of India’s designated green-hydrogen port hubs, supporting the National Green Hydrogen Mission and the development of a new export corridor for low-carbon fuels
Recent development: L&amp;T Energy GreenTech signed a long-term agreement to supply 300,000 tonnes per year of green ammonia from its proposed Kandla plant to Japan’s ITOCHU, mainly for future ammonia bunkering activities.
Risks: High capital costs, renewable-power intermittency, electrolyser availability, desalination and water constraints, ammonia-storage hazards, port infrastructure delays, uncertain future demand and exposure to green-fuel certification rules</description>
