		<Placemark id="0256BA5DAA40214A3860">
			<name>WTI Midland route</name>
			<description>Crude: WTI Midland
API: 40–44°
Sulfur: Below 0.20%, typically around 0.08–0.13%
Type: Light, sweet U.S. crude
Origin: Permian Basin, mainly the Midland Basin in West Texas; transported by pipeline to Gulf Coast export terminals
Markets: Mainly Northwest Europe, the Mediterranean and Asia; Rotterdam is a major pricing and delivery hub
Used for: Gasoline, naphtha, jet fuel, diesel and petrochemical feedstocks
Pricing: Traded against WTI Houston and Dated Brent. Since 2023, qualifying WTI Midland cargoes have been included directly in the Dated Brent benchmark basket
Vessels: Usually Aframax or Suezmax from Texas Gulf Coast terminals; VLCCs may be used for larger export cargoes, sometimes after lightering
Transit: Around 14–18 days from the U.S. Gulf Coast to Rotterdam
Risks: Permian pipeline constraints, Gulf Coast hurricanes, terminal congestion, export-quality variation and dense traffic in the English Channel</description>
