		<Placemark>
			<name>Azeri light route</name>
			<description>Crude: Azeri Light
API: ~35.3–35.6°
Sulfur: ~0.18–0.20%
Type: Light, sweet crude
Origin: Azeri–Chirag–Gunashli fields, offshore Azerbaijan; transported through the BTC pipeline and exported from Ceyhan, Turkey.
Markets: Mediterranean and European refiners, including France, Italy, Croatia and the Netherlands
Used for: Gasoline, naphtha, jet fuel, diesel and petrochemical feedstocks
Pricing: Usually trades at a variable premium or discount to Dated Brent, depending on Mediterranean demand, freight and cargo availability
Vessels: Typically Aframax or Suezmax tankers loaded at Ceyhan
Route to Cressier: Ceyhan → Mediterranean → Fos-sur-Mer → SPSE pipeline → Jura connection → Cressier refinery, Switzerland
Strategic note: Cressier is owned and operated by VAROPreem Energy. SPSE officially supplies the refinery from Fos-sur-Mer through its crude-pipeline network.
Alternative route: Cargoes may continue by sea from Ceyhan through Gibraltar, around Spain and France, through the English Channel and onward to Rotterdam
Transit: Approximately 5–7 days to Fos-sur-Mer; around 12–16 days to Rotterdam
Risks: BTC pipeline outages, Ceyhan loading disruption, Turkish and Mediterranean geopolitical risk, Gibraltar and English Channel congestion, and possible crude-quality contamination</description>
			<styleUrl>#msn_ylw-pushpin</styleUrl>
			<LineString>
				<tessellate>1</tessellate>
				<coordinates>
					35.98573986277994,36.91702865915111,0 35.98798170504674,36.89021848134669,0 35.38945645570686,36.40383227883269,0 32.26778384422678,35.53730982776592,0 27.03265869534856,33.97909360704336,0 14.8267613294643,36.44194146480715,0 7.909933079273721,38.00634017522465,0 4.929033890896786,43.42592324667132,0 
				</coordinates>
			</LineString>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark>
			<name>CPC blend route</name>
			<description>Crude: CPC Blend
API: ~45.3°
Sulfur: ~0.56%
Type: Very light, sweet crude
Origin: Mainly Kazakhstan; transported by the CPC pipeline and exported from the CPC Marine Terminal near Novorossiysk, Russia
Markets: Mainly Mediterranean and Northwest European refiners; also Turkey and selected Asian buyers
Used for: Gasoline, naphtha, jet fuel, diesel and petrochemical feedstocks
Pricing: Usually trades at a variable differential to Dated Brent, depending on Mediterranean demand, freight and Black Sea supply conditions
Vessels: Typically Aframax or Suezmax tankers loaded through offshore single-point moorings
Transit: Around 10–14 days to Rotterdam via the Bosporus, Dardanelles, Mediterranean, Gibraltar and English Channel
Risks: Black Sea security, sanctions exposure, CPC pipeline or terminal outages, weather-related loading delays and congestion in the Turkish Straits</description>
