		<Placemark>
			<name>Arab Light &amp; Arab Super Light route</name>
			<description><![CDATA[Crude: Arab Light & Arab Super Light
API: Arab Light 32–36°; Arab Super Light >40°
Sulfur: Arab Light 1.3–2.2%; Arab Super Light <0.5%
Type: Arab Light is medium, sour crude; Arab Super Light is very light, sweet crude.
Origin: Saudi Arabia; typically exported through Ras Tanura or Juaymah terminals.
Markets: Mainly Asia, with additional sales to Northwest Europe, the Mediterranean and the United States.
Used for: Arab Light provides gasoline, jet fuel, diesel and heavier products; Super Light is especially valuable for naphtha, gasoline, LPG and petrochemical feedstocks.
Pricing: Monthly Saudi Aramco OSP; Northwest European cargoes are priced at a variable differential to ICE Brent, while Asian cargoes are priced against Dubai/Oman.
Vessels: Usually VLCC from Saudi export terminals; Suezmax may be used depending on cargo size, routing and terminal restrictions.
Transit: Around 25–35 days to Rotterdam via the Red Sea and Suez; longer if routed around the Cape of Good Hope.
Risks: Strait of Hormuz disruption, Red Sea security, Bab el-Mandeb and Suez congestion, piracy, war-risk premiums and possible Cape rerouting.]]></description>
			<styleUrl>#msn_icon?color=1976d2&amp;id=2000&amp;scale=4</styleUrl>
			<LineString>
